Scripts:

Contain series of commands
An interpreter executes commands in the script
Anything u can type in the command line, put in a script
Great for automatic task
 
Script does not contain shebang in the command are executed using your shell
Different shells have slightly varying syntex
 
Variables
Syntex : VARIABLE_NAME="Value"
Case sensitive
 
File operators
-d : file is a dir
-e : file exits
-f : file exits in a regular file
-r : file is readable by you
-s : file exits is not empty
-w : file is writable by you
-x : file is executable by you
-z string : is empty
-n string : is not empty
 
Arithmetic operations
Arg1 -eq ag2
 
If condition                 
If ["  "]
Then
Echo "  "
Fi
 
For loop
For VARIABLE_NAME in ITEM_1 ITEM_2
Do
command1
Command 2
done
 
Exit status/return code
0 = 0 Success
Other than 0 = error
Use man r info to find meaning of exit status
 
$? - contains the previously executed code
 
Wildcards
* - Matches 0 r more characters
*.txt
A*
a*.txt
? - matches exactly one character
?.txt
a?
a?.txt
[] - character class
[!] - matches any one of the characters NOT
Ranges characters
[a-g]*
[3-6]*
Named characters classes
[[:alpha:]], alnum, digit, lower, upper, space,
\ - escape character
? - represents the single character
 
Debugging
-x -- prints commands as they execute
Set +x to stop debugging
-e -- exit an error
-v -- prints shell input lines as they are read
Help set | less
 
Sed - stream editor